The basis for this assertion is Clause 6.2 of the Engagement Letter dated July 1, 2020, which stipulates that all disputes arising from the agreement shall be settled under the Rules of the Munich Chamber of Commerce Rules of Arbitration. The respondent emphasizes that there is no agreement to submit disputes to DIS, indicating a lack of consent to DIS jurisdiction.

Elcomponics Sales Pvt. Ltd. ("Respondent") submitted a response to the Request for Arbitration dated 6th May 2025 filed by FAMAS Gmbh. The Respondent raised a jurisdictional objection in its response. The response was submitted on behalf of Elcomponics Sales Pvt. Ltd. by its duly authorized Company Secretary, Anu Sharma, who is authorized to represent the company in this matter. The Respondent contends that the Request for Arbitration is inadmissible and requests that DIS decline jurisdiction over the matter.

The Engagement Letter executed between Elcomponics Sales Pvt. Ltd. and FAMAS Gmbh contains an arbitration agreement. The agreement stipulates that all disputes arising in connection with the agreement shall be finally settled under the Rules of the Munich Chamber of Commerce. This clause provides the framework for resolving any disagreements that may arise from the engagement between the two parties through arbitration proceedings governed by the specified rules.

Famas GmbH initiated arbitration proceedings against Elcomponics Sales. The arbitration is governed by the Rules of IHK Munchen. Elcomponics states that there is no provision in the Engagement Letter permitting submission of disputes to DIS or adoption of DIS procedural rules. Elcomponics claims it never consented to arbitration under DIS rules.

The Respondent contends that the Request for Arbitration is inadmissible because DIS (presumably an arbitration institution) lacks jurisdiction to administer the dispute. The Respondent argues that submitting the dispute to DIS is inconsistent with the parties' agreement and represents an attempt by the Claimant to unilaterally impose a forum not agreed upon in the Engagement Letter. Consequently, the Respondent requests that DIS decline jurisdiction over the matter. The Respondent reserves the right to submit further evidence, arguments, or documentation to support this jurisdictional objection and to engage legal counsel if necessary.
